ladders.explanation:
The brute force approach solves the longest repeated substring problem by systematically examining every possible substring and checking if it appears elsewhere in the string. The intuition is straightforward: if we want to find the longest substring that repeats, we need to consider all substrings from longest to shortest, and for each one, verify if it occurs at least twice. This ensures we find the maximum length solution. The algorithm works by iterating through all possible substring lengths from n-1 down to 1 (starting with longest possible). For each length L, it iterates through all starting positions i from 0 to n-L. For each substring s[i:i+L], it scans the rest of the string from position i+1 to n-L to find a duplicate occurrence. If found, it returns that substring immediately since we're checking from longest to shortest. If no substring of length L repeats, it decreases L and continues. The time complexity is O(n³) because we have three nested loops: length iteration O(n), start position iteration O(n), and duplicate check O(n). Space complexity is O(1) as we only store indices and the result. This approach serves as a baseline for understanding the problem before optimizing with more advanced techniques like suffix arrays or rolling hashes. Common mistakes include not handling edge cases like empty strings or strings with no repeats, and inefficient duplicate checking that doesn't break early. The connection to L1 is that this full solution uses the duplicate checking subroutine as its core component.

Pseudocode:
function longestRepeatedSubstring(s):
    n = length(s)
    for L from n-1 down to 1:
        for i from 0 to n-L:
            substring = s[i:i+L]
            for j from i+1 to n-L:
                if s[j:j+L] == substring:
                    return substring
    return ""  # no repeated substring

Time: O(n³), Space: O(1)

This sub-routine is the heart of the brute force approach. Given a string s and a specific substring defined by start index i and length L, the function checks whether this substring appears at any other position in s. The intuition is that to determine if a substring repeats, we need to compare it with every other possible substring of the same length in the string. The algorithm slides a window of length L through the string starting from position i+1 (to avoid counting the original occurrence) up to n-L. At each position j, it extracts s[j:j+L] and compares it character-by-character with the target substring. If any match is found, it returns true immediately. If no match is found after checking all positions, it returns false. The time complexity is O(n) in worst case where we check nearly all positions, and O(1) in best case if found early. Space complexity is O(1) as we only store indices and temporary variables. This subroutine connects to L0 by being called for every candidate substring in the main algorithm. Common mistakes include off-by-one errors in loop bounds, not handling the case where i+1 might exceed valid positions, and inefficient character-by-character comparison instead of using string slicing. The intuition behind character-by-character comparison is that we need exact match, and early termination on mismatch saves time.

Pseudocode:
function hasDuplicate(s, i, L):
    n = length(s)
    target = s[i:i+L]
    for j from i+1 to n-L:
        match = True
        for k from 0 to L-1:
            if s[j+k] != target[k]:
                match = False
                break
        if match:
            return True
    return False

Time: O(n*L) but L ≤ n, so O(n²) worst case. Space: O(1)

This basic operation is essential for checking if two substrings match. Given two strings a and b, we need to determine if they are identical. The intuition is that strings are equal only if they have the same length and every corresponding character matches. The algorithm first checks if lengths are equal; if not, return false immediately. Then, it iterates through indices from 0 to length-1, comparing a[i] with b[i]. If any mismatch is found, return false. If all characters match, return true. Time complexity is O(L) where L is the length (min length if lengths differ). Space complexity is O(1) as we only use index variables. This connects to L3 as substring extraction often needs comparison. Common mistakes include not checking length first (which can cause index errors or incorrect results), and using reference equality instead of value equality. The intuition for early termination on mismatch is efficiency: we don't need to check further once we find a difference. Real pattern: loop with index comparison.

Pseudocode:
function stringsEqual(a, b):
    if length(a) != length(b):
        return False
    for i from 0 to length(a)-1:
        if a[i] != b[i]:
            return False
    return True

Time: O(L), Space: O(1)
